    {
      "id": "abff48cd_261c34d3",
      "file_path": "components/kpi-computation-ms/src/main/java/org/onap/dcaegen2/kpi/computation/RatioKpiComputation.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 110,
      "message": "There is still a bug here if operand is not assigned a value within the above loop. Probably the easiest fix is to change the operand initialization above to:\n\nString operand = \"\";\n\nAlternatively, test for null explicitly. See the next comment for an alternative that fixes this and another issue.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 105,
        "name": "Tony Hansen",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "tony@att.com",
        "username": "TonyLHansen"
      },
      "updated": "2022-11-29 13:56:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "aa8f3830_ce626c20",
      "file_path": "components/kpi-computation-ms/src/main/java/org/onap/dcaegen2/kpi/computation/RatioKpiComputation.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 114,
      "message": "this log message is not the opposite of the test. I suggest changing the order of tests to:\n\nif (operand == null || operand.isEmpty()) {\n  logger.info(\"operand is empty\");\n} else if (operand.contains(\".\")) {\n  snssai = operand.substring(operand.lastIndexOf(\".\") + 1);\n}\n\nNote that if this is in a tight loop and becomes time-critical, this has the issue that operand is scanning the end of the string twice for \".\". So another formulation would be:\n\nif (operand == null || operand.isEmpty()) {\n  logger.info(\"operand is empty\");\n} else {\n  int dotLocation = operand.lastIndexOf(\".\");\n  if (dotLocation != -1) {\n    snssai = operand.substring(dotLocation + 1);\n  }\n}",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 105,
        "name": "Tony Hansen",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "tony@att.com",
        "username": "TonyLHansen"
      },
      "updated": "2022-11-29 13:56:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
